  <article class="container-prose prose-editorial cs-body" set:html={`<h3><b>Educational Case Study Disclosure</b></h3><p>This case study is hypothetical and for educational purposes only. Scenarios, borrower profiles, loan terms, interest rates, and outcomes are illustrative examples and do not represent current offers or guaranteed terms.</p><p>For specific details including down payment requirements, closing cost estimates, interest rate details, closing cost breakdowns, payment calculations, cash-to-close estimates, or an official Loan Estimate, it is highly recommended you<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a meeting with one of our licensed mortgage advisors</a>.</p><p><b>Learn more:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/24/">Conventional loan cash-out refinance Reg Z advertising requirements (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB official regulation</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1026">Conventional loan cash-out refinance Reg Z full text and compliance</a> – Electronic Code of Federal Regulations</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/interp-24/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official conventional loan cash-out refinance advertising interpretations (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB interpretations</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1014" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Conventional loan cash-out refinance MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertising</a> – Mortgage advertising rules</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/">NMLS Consumer Access – Verify conventional loan cash-out refinance lender licensure</a></li></ul><p>Actual loan terms vary by credit profile, property, occupancy, location, market conditions, and lender guidelines. For current options tailored to you,<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>.</p><p>Ready to explore your options?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor.</p>		
					<h2>How This Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Funded Real Estate Investment While Maintaining Favorable Terms
</h2>				
		<p>Marcus D., a 39-year-old financial advisor based in Fort Lauderdale, had been helping wealthy clients build investment portfolios for over fifteen years. He specialized in retirement planning and wealth accumulation strategies—advising clients on diversification, tax-efficient investing, and long-term asset allocation. Yet despite earning a strong six-figure income and providing expert financial guidance to others, Marcus had never invested in real estate himself.</p><p>Marcus owned a beautiful single-family home in a desirable Fort Lauderdale neighborhood that he'd purchased years earlier. The property had appreciated substantially since his original purchase, and he'd been diligently paying down the mortgage, building significant equity. He'd always intended to invest in real estate but kept postponing—caught up in managing his practice, raising his family, and waiting for the "perfect time" that never seemed to arrive.</p><p>After watching several clients build impressive wealth through rental property portfolios while his own primary residence equity sat idle, Marcus decided it was time to practice what he preached about diversification and wealth building. He wanted to purchase his first investment property—a rental that would generate cash flow, provide tax benefits through depreciation, and begin building the real estate portfolio he'd been planning for years. The challenge was funding the down payment without liquidating his investment accounts or depleting his emergency reserves.</p><p>That's when Marcus considered a conventional cash-out refinance—accessing his substantial home equity to fund his first rental property purchase while maintaining his primary residence financing at competitive conventional loan rates.</p><p><b>Facing similar challenges?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to explore your options.</p><h2><b>The Challenge: Finding Capital to Fund First Investment Property Purchase</b></h2><p>Marcus had spent months analyzing rental properties in growing Fort Lauderdale submarkets. He'd identified a perfect first investment—a three-bedroom condo near major hospital systems that would attract traveling nurses and healthcare professionals seeking furnished rentals. The numbers worked beautifully: attractive rental income relative to the purchase price, strong occupancy rates in the area, and excellent long-term appreciation potential.</p><h3><b>How Do Investors Fund Real Estate Down Payments?</b></h3><p>The obstacle was the down payment. Investment property financing typically requires substantial down payments—significantly more than primary residence purchases. Marcus had the capital available in various forms, but each option presented challenges. He could liquidate taxable investment accounts, but that would trigger capital gains taxes and interrupt compound growth in portfolios that were performing well. He could drain his cash reserves, but that would leave him without appropriate emergency funds for both his primary residence and potential unexpected expenses with the rental property.</p><p>"I advise my clients never to liquidate performing investments unless absolutely necessary," Marcus explained. "Taking substantial capital gains hits to fund a down payment seemed counterproductive when I had significant equity sitting in my primary residence. I needed a more efficient way to access capital for investment purposes without disrupting my existing investment strategy or compromising my emergency reserves."</p><h3><b>What Is a Conventional Loan Cash-Out Refinance?</b></h3><p>Marcus explored personal loans, but rates were significantly higher than mortgage financing and terms were much shorter—creating expensive monthly payments that would reduce cash flow from the rental property. He investigated home equity loans and HELOCs, which were possibilities, but he also recognized that his current primary residence mortgage rate was higher than current market rates. A conventional cash-out refinance could potentially accomplish two goals simultaneously: access equity for the investment property down payment AND reduce his primary residence interest rate.</p><p>The concept was straightforward—refinance his primary residence for more than the current mortgage balance, pocket the difference to fund the rental property purchase, and ideally secure a better rate on his primary residence in the process. But Marcus had concerns about execution and long-term financial implications.</p><h3><b>How Do Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Rates Compare to Current Mortgages?</b></h3><p>First, he wanted to ensure he could secure competitive conventional loan rates on the cash-out refinance. Some cash-out refinances carry higher rates than standard rate-and-term refinances because lenders view them as slightly higher risk. Marcus wanted confirmation that his excellent credit, substantial income, strong equity position, and stable employment history would qualify him for favorable conventional cash-out refinance rates.</p><p>Second, Marcus worried about loan-to-value limitations. Conventional cash-out refinances have maximum LTV ratios—meaning lenders won't let borrowers access every dollar of equity. Marcus needed to calculate exactly how much equity he could access while staying within conventional loan guidelines and maintaining comfortable equity cushion in his primary residence.</p><h3><b>What Are the Tax Implications of Conventional Cash-Out Refinancing?</b></h3><p>Third, he wanted to understand tax implications. Marcus knew that mortgage interest on primary residences is generally tax-deductible, but what about interest on a cash-out refinance used to purchase investment property? He needed clarity on how to properly structure and document the transaction to maximize legitimate tax benefits while ensuring full compliance with IRS regulations.</p><p>"As a financial advisor, I'm careful about tax efficiency," Marcus said. "I needed to understand exactly how a conventional cash-out refinance for investment property purchase would be treated for tax purposes. I wanted to structure everything properly from the beginning—correct documentation, appropriate allocation of interest deductions, and compliance with all applicable regulations."</p><h3><b>How Long Does Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Approval Take?</b></h3><p>Fourth, Marcus faced timing pressure. The investment property he'd identified was attracting interest from other buyers. He needed financing that could close quickly once his offer was accepted—not a lengthy process that might cause him to lose the property to faster-moving competitors. He wanted to know whether a conventional cash-out refinance could be completed efficiently enough to support his investment property timeline.</p><p><b>Experiencing similar challenges accessing capital for investments?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to discuss alternative strategies.</p><h2><b>The Discovery: How Marcus Found Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Solutions</b></h2><p>Marcus consulted with a conventional loan specialist who had extensive experience working with investors and high-net-worth professionals. The loan advisor understood Marcus's dual goals: access equity for investment property purchase while optimizing his primary residence financing.</p><h3><b>Why Use Conventional Cash-Out Refinance for Investment Property?</b></h3><p>The conventional loan specialist explained that cash-out refinancing is a common and effective strategy for accessing home equity to fund investment property purchases. The key advantages include: competitive rates if the borrower has strong financial qualifications, ability to access substantial equity while maintaining appropriate LTV ratios, potentially better rates than the current mortgage if market conditions are favorable, and significantly more favorable terms than personal loans or credit cards.</p><p>"That conversation validated my initial thinking," Marcus explained. "The conventional loan advisor confirmed that cash-out refinancing was a smart strategy for accessing equity to fund investment property purchases—especially for someone like me with excellent credit, strong income, and substantial existing equity. She explained that I could likely secure favorable conventional cash-out refinance rates while accessing enough capital to fund the rental property down payment comfortably."</p><h3><b>How Much Equity Can You Access Through Conventional Cash-Out Refinance?</b></h3><p>The conventional cash-out refinance lender walked through LTV calculations. Conventional cash-out refinances typically allow borrowers to access equity up to specific LTV thresholds—meaning Marcus could access a substantial portion of his equity while maintaining appropriate cushion in his primary residence. The exact amount would depend on his home's current appraised value, his existing mortgage balance, and conventional loan guidelines.</p><p>Marcus appreciated that the conventional cash-out refinance process would include a fresh appraisal of his primary residence. Given strong appreciation in his neighborhood since his original purchase, Marcus was confident the appraisal would support accessing sufficient equity for his investment property down payment while staying well within conventional loan LTV limits.</p><h3><b>What Documentation Do Conventional Cash-Out Refinances Require?</b></h3><p>The conventional loan specialist also explained documentation requirements. Cash-out refinances require the same comprehensive documentation as purchase mortgages—income verification, credit evaluation, asset documentation, and property appraisal. For Marcus, with his stable W-2 income from his financial advisory practice, excellent credit, and substantial assets, the documentation process would be straightforward.</p><p>Importantly, the conventional cash-out refinance lender explained that borrowers don't need to specify exactly how they'll use cash-out proceeds—though Marcus's plan to invest in rental property was a financially sound strategy that strengthened his overall application by demonstrating sophisticated wealth-building focus rather than cash-out for debt consolidation or consumption.</p><h3><b>How Are Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Tax Benefits Structured?</b></h3><p>Regarding tax implications, the conventional loan advisor recommended Marcus consult his CPA for specific tax advice but explained general principles. Mortgage interest is generally deductible on primary residences up to certain limits. When cash-out proceeds fund investment property purchases, the interest allocation can become more complex—requiring proper documentation and potentially involving his tax professional to ensure correct treatment. Marcus appreciated the guidance to involve his CPA in the planning process from the beginning.</p><p>"The conventional cash-out refinance lender didn't just approve a loan—she helped me think strategically about the entire transaction," Marcus said. "She explained how to structure the refinance efficiently, discussed tax considerations to explore with my CPA, and confirmed that my wealth-building strategy was sound. This was partnership, not just transaction processing."</p><h2><b>The Solution: Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Approval and Investment Property Purchase</b></h2><p>Marcus worked with his conventional cash-out refinance specialist to structure financing for his primary residence that would access equity for his investment property purchase. The process focused on his excellent credit, strong professional income, substantial existing equity, and sound investment strategy.</p><h3><b>What Is the Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Application Process?</b></h3><p><b>Documentation provided:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Strong stable W-2 income from established financial advisory practice</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Excellent credit score with spotless payment history</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Substantial equity in primary residence from appreciation and paydown</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Comprehensive asset documentation showing investment accounts and reserves</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Low debt-to-income ratio with minimal consumer debt</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Clean payment history on current mortgage</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Investment property purchase contract demonstrating intended use of proceeds</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Strong financial profile demonstrating capacity to manage both mortgages comfortably</li></ul><p><b>The approval process:</b></p><ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Initial consultation</b> – Discussed conventional cash-out refinance strategy and goals</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Property valuation</b> – Current market value estimated to calculate available equity</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Loan structure analysis</b> – Determined optimal loan amount balancing equity access and LTV ratios</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Rate quote</b> – Provided competitive conventional cash-out refinance rates based on Marcus's strong profile</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Application submission</b> – Completed comprehensive cash-out refinance application</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Document gathering</b> – Assembled income, asset, and credit documentation</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Credit review</b> – Verified excellent credit history</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Income verification</b> – Confirmed stable professional income capacity</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Property appraisal</b> – Licensed appraiser valued primary residence at strong amount supporting equity access</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Underwriting review</b> – Evaluated Marcus's capacity to manage both primary residence and investment property mortgages</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Conditional approval</b> – Approved subject to standard conditions</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Investment property offer</b> – Marcus made offer on rental property, accepted by seller</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Final approval</b> – All conditions cleared for cash-out refinance</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Closing</b> – Marcus closed on conventional cash-out refinance, accessing equity for investment</li></ol><p>The conventional cash-out refinance lender evaluated Marcus's overall financial capacity—not just his ability to carry the new primary residence mortgage, but his ability to manage both that mortgage AND the upcoming investment property mortgage comfortably. Marcus's strong income, excellent credit, minimal existing debt, and substantial reserves demonstrated clear capacity to handle both properties successfully.</p><h3><b>How Do Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Appraisals Work?</b></h3><p>The property appraisal confirmed Marcus's home had appreciated substantially since his original purchase. The strong appraised value, combined with his existing mortgage paydown, meant Marcus had significant equity available within conventional loan LTV limits. He could access more than enough capital to fund his investment property down payment while maintaining comfortable equity cushion in his primary residence.</p><p>The conventional cash-out refinance lender offered competitive rates reflecting Marcus's strong financial profile. While the rate was slightly higher than standard rate-and-term refinance rates due to the cash-out nature, it was still quite favorable—especially compared to personal loan alternatives or depleting investment accounts with tax consequences.</p><p><b>Exploring refinance?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/refinance-or-heloc-inquiry/"> Submit a refinance inquiry</a> to compare your options.</p><h2><b>The Results: Marcus Funds His First Investment Property Through Conventional Cash-Out Refinance</b></h2><p>Marcus closed on his conventional cash-out refinance and received substantial proceeds at closing. He immediately used those funds for the down payment on his first rental property—the three-bedroom condo near Fort Lauderdale hospital systems. Within weeks, he closed on the investment property and had it rented to a traveling nurse on a long-term contract.</p><h3><b>What Results Did Marcus Achieve with This Conventional Cash-Out Refinance?</b></h3><p><b>Final outcome:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Accessed substantial home equity through conventional cash-out refinance at competitive rates</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Funded investment property down payment without liquidating performing investment accounts</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Maintained appropriate emergency reserves without depletion</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Avoided capital gains taxes from investment account liquidation</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Competitive conventional cash-out refinance rate based on excellent credit and strong financial profile</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Timeline: From application to closing in reasonable timeframe</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Investment property: 3BR/2BA condo near major hospital systems, Fort Lauderdale, FL</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Rental outcome: Immediately rented to healthcare professional at attractive monthly rate</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Long-term plan: Build portfolio of five rental properties over next decade creating passive income streams for early retirement</li></ul><h3><b>How Does Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Compare to Alternative Funding Methods?</b></h3><p><b>Alternative funding methods vs. conventional cash-out refinance:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Liquidating investment accounts:</b> Capital gains taxes and interrupted compound growth</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Depleting cash reserves:</b> No emergency cushion and reduced financial flexibility</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Personal loans:</b> Significantly higher rates and shorter terms reducing cash flow</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Credit cards or HELOCs:</b> Variable rates creating unpredictable costs</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Conventional cash-out refinance:</b> Competitive fixed rate, accessed substantial capital efficiently ✓</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Investment strategy:</b> PRESERVED ✓</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Emergency reserves:</b> MAINTAINED ✓</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Tax efficiency:</b> OPTIMIZED ✓</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Wealth building:</b> ACCELERATED ✓</li></ul><p>"The conventional cash-out refinance was the most efficient way to access capital for my first rental property purchase," Marcus explained. "I avoided liquidating investment accounts and triggering capital gains. I kept my emergency reserves intact. I secured competitive financing that made the investment property cash flow strong. Most importantly, I finally started building the rental property portfolio I'd been planning for years—using my home equity strategically rather than letting it sit idle."</p><h3><b>What Are Marcus's Long-Term Real Estate Wealth-Building Plans?</b></h3><p>Marcus views this first rental property as the beginning of a systematic real estate portfolio strategy. His goal is to acquire five rental properties over the next decade—properties that will generate substantial passive income streams supplementing his financial advisory income and funding early retirement or reduced work schedules in his fifties.</p><p>The conventional cash-out refinance demonstrated how to use primary residence equity strategically to fund investment property acquisitions. As Marcus builds equity in his rental properties through tenant payments and appreciation, he plans to use additional financing strategies to continue scaling his portfolio—potentially 1031 exchanges, cash-out refinances on the rental properties themselves, or additional equity access from his primary residence if appropriate.</p><p>Marcus's financial advisor expertise now extends to his personal real estate investing. He's applying the same diversification, risk management, and long-term wealth-building principles he teaches clients—but now across both traditional investment portfolios AND rental property holdings. This multi-asset-class approach creates more robust wealth accumulation than either strategy alone.</p><p>When he's ready to purchase rental properties two, three, four, and five, Marcus may use<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc"> HELOC</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan"> Home Equity Loan</a> financing to access equity more efficiently—allowing him to tap appreciation in both his primary residence and existing rental properties for new acquisitions without refinancing and losing favorable rates on existing mortgages.</p><p>"This conventional cash-out refinance was property #1 in what will become a five-property portfolio," Marcus said. "I'm building passive income that will fund my retirement, create generational wealth for my family, and prove to my financial advisory clients that I practice what I preach about real estate investing. This first cash-out refinance unlocked the strategy—now I'm executing systematically toward my long-term wealth goals."</p><p><b>Ready to get started?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> Get approved</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a call</a> to discuss your situation.</p><h2><b>Exploring Other Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Options?</b></h2><p>While Marcus used conventional cash-out refinance to fund investment property purchase, cash-out refinancing works for multiple scenarios:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Need rate reduction too? See how borrowers use<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/conventional-loan-refinance"> conventional refinance for rate and term improvements</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Building new home? See how families use<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/conventional-construction-loan"> conventional construction loans for custom builds</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> to find success stories matching your situation</li></ul><h2><b>Key Takeaways for Real Estate Investors</b></h2><p><b>What Can Investors Learn from This Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Success?</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Conventional cash-out refinance provides efficient equity access for investment property purchases</b>—competitive rates for strong financial profiles make this strategy more cost-effective than personal loans, credit cards, or liquidating investment accounts (<a href="https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/media/9391/display">Fannie Mae cash-out refinance guidelines</a>)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>LTV limits govern how much equity can be accessed</b>—conventional cash-out refinances allow substantial equity access while maintaining appropriate cushion, protecting both borrower and lender</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Excellent credit and strong financial profiles unlock favorable rates</b>—strong credit scores, stable income, low debt-to-income ratios, and substantial reserves qualify borrowers for competitive conventional cash-out refinance rates</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Strategy preserves investment account growth and avoids capital gains</b>—accessing home equity for investment property down payments prevents liquidating performing portfolios and triggering substantial tax liabilities</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Tax implications require professional guidance</b>—consult CPAs regarding proper documentation and allocation of mortgage interest deductions when cash-out proceeds fund investment property purchases</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Timing can be efficient for investment property acquisitions</b>—conventional cash-out refinances can close in reasonable timeframes supporting investment property purchase timelines in competitive markets</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Think beyond the single transaction</b>—successful investors use conventional cash-out refinances strategically as part of larger portfolio-building plans, leveraging primary residence equity to fund multiple rental property acquisitions over time, creating passive income streams for financial independence and generational wealth building</li></ul><p><b>Have questions about conventional cash-out refinance for investment purposes?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor experienced in investor financing.</p><h2><b>Alternative Loan Programs for Equity Access</b></h2><p>If a conventional cash-out refinance isn't the perfect fit, consider these alternatives:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc">HELOC</a> – Flexible line of credit secured by home equity</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan">Home Equity Loan</a> – Fixed-rate second mortgage for lump sum equity access</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-refinance">Conventional Refinance</a> – Rate-and-term refinance without cash-out if equity access not needed</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loans">DSCR Loan</a> – Investment property financing based on rental income</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loans">Portfolio Loan</a> – Flexible financing for multiple investment properties</li></ul><p><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">Explore all loan programs</a> to find your best option.</p><h2><b>Helpful Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Resources</b></h2><p><b>Learn more about this loan program:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/conventional-cash-out-refinance">Complete Conventional Cash-Out Refinance Guide</a> - Detailed requirements and strategies</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/cash-out-refinance-calculator">Cash-Out Refinance Calculator</a> - Estimate equity access and new payments</li></ul><p><b>Similar success stories:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/conventional-cash-out-refinance-investment">How a financial advisor used conventional cash-out refinance to fund first rental property</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/conventional-cash-out-refinance-portfolio">Investor accesses equity for portfolio expansion through cash-out refinancing</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> - Browse by investment strategy and goals</li></ul><p><b>External authoritative resources:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://singlefamily.fanniemae.com/media/9391/display">Fannie Mae cash-out refinance guidelines</a> - Official conventional cash-out refinance standards</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p936">IRS mortgage interest deduction guidance</a> - Tax considerations for mortgage interest</li></ul><p><b>Ready to get started?</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/">Apply online</a> - Start your application</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/">Schedule a consultation</a> - Discuss your equity access strategy</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/discovery-quiz/">Take the discovery quiz</a> - Find the right financing solution</li></ul><p><b>Need local expertise?</b><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/get-a-local-introduction/"> Get introduced to trusted partners</a> including CPAs, real estate attorneys, and investment property specialists.</p>		
